In (<!--\ref{ware1}-->a) we can see both an A prefix and a P suffix (since both feminine third person and first person are overtly marked), but in the next two examples only one argument is marked: the P argument in (<!--\ref{ware1}-->b) and the A argument in (<!--\ref{ware1}-->c) are third person non-feminine singular and therefore get zero marking.

At first glance, Warekena exhibits a classic case of split intransitivity: There is a class of Sa verbs that always get prefix marking and a class of Sp verbs that are always marked by suffixes.[^ware-o-p] What is cross-linguistically remarkable, however, is the domain of the split. Verbs such as *go*, which are volitional and dynamic, are of course Sa verbs, but many verbs that would be marked as Sp in other split intransitive languages, are Sa verbs in Warekena, such as *die*, which is non-agentive and would be marked as Sp e.g. in Lakhota, or *lie*, which is stative and would be an Sp verb in languages like Guaraní. Consider:

