     bad-COS=3SG.M
\glt `It is bad.'
\glend
\end{enumerate}
\end{examples}
-->

This seeems like a contrived argument to me, however. Distinctions between verbs and other word classes, especially adjectives, are not obvious in many languages if they exist at all, and, as mentioned before, [#aikhenvald98;] explicitly states that their boundaries are fuzzy in Warekena. From the examples provided it might seem as if Baure has a more explicit distinction since nonverbal roots appear either with a copular or with a "change of state" suffix, but then how does that explain the presence of the suffix both on Sa verbs (<!--\ref{baure-non-sp}-->) and Sp verbs (<!--\ref{baure-sp}-->)? I fail to see a principled difference between 'cold', 'tired' and 'bad' and why the former two could be called examples of stative verbs and the latter an adjective. In any case, <!--\citeauthor{baure-kurri}--> do not discuss this issue. It is therefore hard to understand what the split in argument marking really consists of. It may be that the split intransitive pattern in Baure is retreating and that the proclitic marking is being generalised, such that more and more former Sp verbs are used as Sa verbs, but without more examples it is hard to tell; the split in Baure appears therefore to be quite idiosyncratic in nature (although this only concerns property verbs; non-property verbs are always Sa verbs as in other Arawak languages).

